There must be a future vision of God1. We are not told how this is to be reconciled with the distinction which the writer maintains‚ in respect of invisibility, between the Father and the Son: he does not even raise the point, but perhaps he would find the reconciliation in the thought of an inconceivable development of man's spiritual faculty, such as the words of c. xviii may imply (‘gradatim enim et per incrementa fragilitas humana nutriri debuit per imaginem ad istam gloriam, ut deum patrem uidere possit aliquando2'). We may also refer to what is said below (g 6) on the ‘Deification of man3.'

Something must also be said upon the obedience of the Son, and it enters into Novatian's conception of His Divinity. He is ‘oboediens patri qua filius4'3 He obeys and ever has obeyed the Father in all things⁵; He holds the power over all things, but by the consignment and sufferance of His Father (‘sed qua traditam, sed qua concessam, sed qua a patre proprio sibi indultamss’). The expression ‘famulus' in ch. x⁷ is another very strong assertion of this relationship of subjection.
